          "content": "Good, I can read the PDF fully. Now let me look at your code one more time carefully before giving you my analysis.\n\nThe PDF is clear. Here's my full analysis of what you have, what's wrong, and what needs to be done — with reasons for everything:\n\n---\n\n## Current state vs. what's needed\n\n### 1. Struct ordering bug in `cub3d.h`\n\n`t_scene` uses `t_parser` before `t_parser` is declared. C reads top to bottom — the compiler will error. Fix: move `t_parser` above `t_scene`.\n\n---\n\n### 2. The parser doesn't parse the config section at all\n\nRight now `parse_config` reads every line into `map.grid` — including `NO ./texture`, `F 220,100,0`, etc. That's wrong. The `.cub` file has two distinct sections:\n\n- **Config section**: `NO`, `SO`, `WE`, `EA`, `F`, `C` — can be in any order, separated by empty lines, must come before the map\n- **Map section**: always last, spaces are valid map characters\n\nYou need to detect which lines are config identifiers and which lines are the map. The map starts at the first line that contains only valid map characters (`0`, `1`, `N`, `S`, `E`, `W`, ` `).\n\n---\n\n### 3. `parser.col` is set wrong\n\n```c\nscene->parser.col = ft_strlen((scene->map.grid[0]) - 1);\n```\nThe parenthesis is misplaced — this does `(pointer - 1)` then `ft_strlen`, not `ft_strlen(string) - 1`. Should be:\n```c\nscene->parser.col = ft_strlen(scene->map.grid[0]) - 1; // -1 to strip \\n\n```\nBut also: `grid[0]` at that point is a config line like `NO ./texture`, not the map. Width should be computed from the map rows only.\n\n---\n\n### 4. `check_borders` is naive and will fail\n\nThe subject says spaces are valid map characters and maps are not necessarily rectangular. Your current border check assumes every row has the same width (`parser.col`) and that every cell on row 0/last row must be `'1'`. A map like the one in the PDF has rows of different lengths. This will segfault or give false errors.\n\nThe correct approach for phase 2 is **flood fill** from the player position — if the fill ever reaches an out-of-bounds cell or a space, the map isn't closed. This replaces the naive border check entirely.\n\n---\n\n### 5. `map_validation` runs on the whole grid including config lines\n\nSince you store everything in `map.grid`, validation is running on lines like `NO ./path` and `F 220,100,0`. Those will trigger \"Invalid character in the map file\".\n\n---\n\n### 6. `init_mlx` doesn't exist\n\nCalled in `main.c` but never implemented. Won't compile.\n\n---\n\n### 7. No test `.cub` file\n\nYou can't run anything without one. You need at least a minimal valid map in `maps/`.\n\n---\n\n## What I suggest building, in order\n\n**Step 1 — Fix the header** (struct ordering)\n\n**Step 2 — Rewrite the parser in two passes:**\n- Pass 1: scan lines, parse config identifiers (`NO`, `SO`, `WE`, `EA`, `F`, `C`), skip empty lines, stop when map starts\n- Pass 2: from where the map starts, read remaining lines into `map.grid`\n\nThis is the cleanest split and matches exactly what the subject describes.\n\n**Step 3 — Parse colors properly**\n`F 220,100,0` → split by comma, validate each value is 0–255, store in `t_color`.\n\n**Step 4 — Normalize the map (pad rows to same width)**\nAfter reading map rows, find the longest row, pad shorter ones with spaces. This makes the grid rectangular and makes everything downstream (raycasting, validation) much simpler for your colleague.\n\n**Step 5 — Replace border check with flood fill**\nThis is the correct and subject-compliant way to validate the map is closed.\n\n**Step 6 — Add a stub `init_mlx`** so it compiles and opens a window.\n\n**Step 7 — Add a test map** in `maps/` so you can actually run it.\n\n---\n\nWant me to start with Step 1 and 2 (fix header + rewrite the parser split)? I'll explain each piece as I write it."
