                    "Text": "============================\nCUB3D - PARSER NOTES\n============================\n\n--- STEP 1: Fix struct ordering in cub3d.h ---\n\nPROBLEM:\n  In C, structs must be declared before they are used.\n  t_scene used t_parser inside it, but t_parser was declared AFTER t_scene.\n  This causes a compile error: \"unknown type name t_parser\".\n\nFIX:\n  Move t_parser definition ABOVE t_scene in cub3d.h.\n\nRULE TO REMEMBER:\n  In C headers, always declare types in dependency order:\n  if A uses B, B must come first.\n\n---\n\n--- STEP 2: Rewrite the parser (two-phase approach) ---\n\nA .cub file has two sections:\n  1. CONFIG section: NO, SO, WE, EA, F, C — any order, empty lines allowed between\n  2. MAP section: always last, no empty lines allowed inside it\n\nHOW TO DETECT WHERE MAP STARTS:\n  A config line always starts with a 2-char identifier (NO/SO/WE/EA)\n  or a 1-char identifier (F/C) followed by a space.\n  A map line contains ONLY: '0' '1' 'N' 'S' 'E' 'W' ' ' '\\n'\n  So: if a line is non-empty and is NOT a known identifier -> it's a map line.\n\nPARSING FLOW (line by line):\n  - map not started yet:\n      - empty line -> skip\n      - starts with NO/SO/WE/EA/F/C -> parse as config\n      - anything else -> map has started, treat as first map row\n  - map started:\n      - empty line -> map has ended (no empty lines allowed inside map)\n      - non-empty -> add to map grid\n      - after map ended, any non-empty line -> error\n\nFILES:\n  main_parse.c   -> coordinates the loop, decides config vs map\n  parse_config.c -> handles NO/SO/WE/EA/F/C line parsing\n  map_validation.c -> stays as is for now, will be improved in phase 2\n\nRULE TO REMEMBER:\n  The map must be the LAST element. Once map starts, config is closed.\n  Empty lines inside the map = error.\n  Spaces inside the map = valid characters (not empty lines).\n\n---\n"
