          "message_id": "fb68dfe2-7d25-4a28-b8fa-2e48f8cd9792",
          "content": "Good question. Here's the purpose in plain terms.\n\n---\n\n**The problem flood fill solves:**\n\nThe subject says the map must be \"closed/surrounded by walls\". That means the player can never walk into an open edge or out of bounds.\n\nYour current validation only checks that characters are valid (`0 1 N S E W space`). It does **not** check if the map is actually enclosed.\n\nFor example, this map would pass your current validation but is invalid:\n\n```\n111111\n100001\n10N000    <- open on the right, player can escape\n100001\n111111\n```\n\n**What flood fill does:**\n\nStarting from the player's position, it simulates walking into every reachable `0` cell in all 4 directions. For each cell it visits, it checks:\n\n- Am I out of bounds? → **error**, map isn't closed\n- Am I a space? → **error**, space on a reachable cell means there's a hole\n\nIf the fill completes without hitting either of those → the map is properly enclosed and valid.\n\n**Why not just check borders?**\n\nA map like this has valid borders but a hole inside:\n\n```\n1111111\n1000001\n1011101\n100 001   <- space in the middle, reachable by player\n1011101\n1000001\n1111111\n```\n\nA border check would pass this. Flood fill would catch it.\n\n---\n\nThat's it. It's essentially: *\"can the player reach somewhere they shouldn't?\"* — if yes, error. Ready to implement it?"
        }
